  childSummary:"An elevator is like a giant seesaw! On one end of a strong steel cable is the elevator cab (the box you ride in), and on the other end is a heavy block called a COUNTERWEIGHT. The counterweight weighs the same as the cab plus half the maximum passengers — so the system is almost balanced! The motor only needs to push the small DIFFERENCE (like gently tipping a balanced seesaw), not lift the whole heavy cab. What about safety? An elevator has 6-8 steel cables, and EACH ONE can hold the entire cab alone — so ALL of them would have to break at once (which has never happened in history!). Plus, if the cab goes too fast, a special device called a GOVERNOR triggers emergency brakes that GRAB the metal rails and stop the cab — making it physically impossible to fall. Elevators are actually the SAFEST way to travel — safer than walking!",
